[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Reducing the cost of software maintenance is the most often cited reason for following coding conventions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Software peer review frequently involves reading source code.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] This type of peer review is primarily a defect detection activity.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] By definition, only the original author of a piece of code has read the source file before the code is submitted for review.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Code that is written using consistent guidelines is easier for other reviewers to understand and assimilate, improving the efficacy of the defect detection process.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Even for the original author, consistently coded software eases maintainability.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] There is no guarantee that an individual will remember the precise rationale for why a particular piece of code was written in a certain way long after the code was originally written.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Consistent use of whitespace improves readability and reduces the time it takes to understand the software.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Where coding conventions have been specifically designed to produce high-quality code, and have then been formally adopted, they then become coding standards.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Specific styles, irrespective of whether they are commonly adopted, do not automatically produce good quality code.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Complexity is a factor going against security.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] The management of complexity includes the following basic principle: minimize the amount of code written during the project development.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] This prevents unnecessary work which prevents unnecessary cost, both upfront and downstream.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] This is simply because if there is less code, it is less work not only to create the application, but also to maintain it.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Complexity is managed both at the design stage (how the project is architectured) and at the development stage (by having simpler code).
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] If the coding is kept basic and simple then the complexity will be minimised.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Very often this is keeping the coding as 'physical' as possible - coding in a manner that is very direct and not highly abstract.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] This produces optimal code that is easy to read and follow.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Complexity can also be avoided simply by not using complicated tools for simple jobs.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] The more complex the code is the more likely it is to be buggy, the more difficult the bugs are to find and the more likely there are to be hidden bugs.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Refactoring refers to a software maintenance activity where source code is modified to improve readability or improve its structure.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Software is often refactored to bring it into conformance with a team's stated coding standards after its initial release.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Any change that does not alter the behavior of the software can be considered refactoring.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Common refactoring activities are changing variable names, renaming methods, moving methods or whole classes and breaking large methods (or functions) into smaller ones.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Agile software development methodologies plan for regular (or even continuous) refactoring making it an integral part of the team software development process.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Coding conventions allow programmers to have simple scripts or programs whose job is to process source code for some purpose other than compiling it into an executable.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] It is common practice to count the software size (Source lines of code) to track current project progress or establish a baseline for future project estimates.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Consistent coding standards can, in turn, make the measurements more consistent.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Special tags within source code comments are often used to process documentation, two notable examples are javadoc and doxygen.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] The tools specify the use of a set of tags, but their use within a project is determined by convention.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Coding conventions simplify writing new software whose job is to process existing software.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Use of static code analysis has grown consistently since the 1950s.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Some of the growth of this class of development tools stems from increased maturity and sophistication of the practitioners themselves (and the modern focus on safety and security), but also from the nature of the languages themselves.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] All software practitioners must grapple with the problem of organizing and managing a large number of sometimes complex instructions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] For all but the smallest software projects, source code (instructions) are partitioned into separate files and frequently among many directories.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] It was natural for programmers to collect closely related functions (behaviors) in the same file and to collect related files into directories.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] As software development shifted from purely procedural programming (such as found in FORTRAN) towards more object-oriented constructs (such as found in C++), it became the practice to write the code for a single (public) class in a single file (the 'one class per file' convention).
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Java has gone one step further - the Java compiler returns an error if it finds more than one public class per file.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] A convention in one language may be a requirement in another.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Language conventions also affect individual source files.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Each compiler (or interpreter) used to process source code is unique.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] The rules a compiler applies to the source creates implicit standards.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] For example, Python code is much more consistently indented than, say Perl, because whitespace (indentation) is actually significant to the interpreter.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Python does not use the brace syntax Perl uses to delimit functions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Changes in indentation serve as the delimiters.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] The reason is that in Tcl, curly braces are not used only to delimit functions as in C or Java.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] More generally, curly braces are used to group words together into a single argument.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] In Tcl, the *word* **while** takes two arguments, a *condition* and an *action*.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] In the example above, **while** is missing its second argument, its *action* (because the Tcl also uses the newline character to delimit the end of a command).
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] There are a large number of coding conventions; see *Coding Style* for numerous examples and discussion.
[src:pre-commit-framework/coding-conventions] Coding standards include the CERT C Coding Standard, MISRA C, High Integrity C++.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:pre-commit-framework/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Design goals of Git include speed, data integrity, and support for distributed, non-linear workflows—thousands of parallel branches running on different computers.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] As with most other distributed version control systems, and unlike most client–server systems, Git maintains a local copy of the entire repository, also known as the "repo", with history and version-tracking abilities, independent of network access or a central server.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] A repository is stored on each computer in a standard directory with additional, hidden files to provide version control capabilities.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git provides features to synchronize changes between repositories that share history; for asynchronous collaboration, this extends to repositories on remote machines.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Although all repositories (with the same history) are peers, developers often use a central server to host a repository to hold an integrated copy.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Today, Git is the version control system most commonly used by software developers.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] It is the most popular distributed version control system, with nearly 95% of developers reporting it as their primary version control system as of 2022.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] It is the most widely used source-code management tool among professional developers.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Several different software forges offer Git repository services, including GitHub, SourceForge, Bitbucket and GitLab.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git is free and open-source software shared under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The trademark "Git" is registered by the Software Freedom Conservancy.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Torvalds started developing Git in April 2005 after the free license for BitKeeper, the proprietary source-control management (SCM) system used for Linux kernel development since 2002, was revoked for Linux.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The copyright holder of BitKeeper, Larry McVoy, claimed that Andrew Tridgell had created SourcePuller by reverse engineering the BitKeeper protocols.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The same incident also spurred the creation of Mercurial, another version-control system.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Torvalds wanted a distributed system that he could use like BitKeeper, but none of the available free systems met his needs.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] He cited an example of a source-control management system needing 30 seconds to apply a patch and update all associated metadata, and noted that this would not scale to the needs of Linux kernel development, where synchronizing with fellow maintainers could require 250 such actions at once.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] These criteria eliminated every version-control system in use at the time, so immediately after the 2.6.12-rc2 Linux kernel development release, Torvalds set out to write his own.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The development of Git began on 3 April 2005.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Torvalds announced the project on 6 April and became self-hosting the next day.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The first merge of multiple branches took place on 18 April.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Torvalds achieved his performance goals; on 29 April, the nascent Git was benchmarked recording patches to the Linux kernel tree at a rate of 6.7 patches per second.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] On 16 June, Git managed the kernel 2.6.12 release.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Torvalds turned over maintenance on 26 July 2005 to Junio Hamano, a major contributor to the project.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Hamano was responsible for the 1.0 release on 21 December 2005.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Torvalds quipped about the name *git* (which is British English slang for an unpleasant or silly person): "I'm an egotistical bastard, and I name all my projects after myself.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] First 'Linux', now 'git'." The man page describes Git as "the stupid content tracker".
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The source code for Git refers to the program as "the information manager from hell".
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git's design is a synthesis of Torvalds's experience with Linux in maintaining a large distributed development project, along with his intimate knowledge of file-system performance gained from the same project and the urgent need to produce a working system in short order.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git supports rapid branching and merging, and includes specific tools for visualizing and navigating a non-linear development history.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] In Git, a core assumption is that a change will be merged more often than it is written, as it is passed around to various reviewers.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] In Git, branches are very lightweight: a branch is only a reference to one commit.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] , Git gives each developer a local copy of the full development history, and changes are copied from one such repository to another.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] These changes are imported as added development branches and can be merged in the same way as a locally developed branch.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git also has a CVS server emulation, which enables the use of existing CVS clients and IDE plugins to access Git repositories.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] repositories can be used directly with git-svn.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] ; fetching version history from a locally stored repository can be one hundred times faster than fetching it from the remote server.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] in Git terms) depends upon the complete development history leading up to that commit.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Once it is published, it is not possible to change the old versions without it being noticed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] , but with added data at the nodes and leaves.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] and several shell scripts that provide wrappers around those programs.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Although most of those scripts have since been rewritten in C for speed and portability, the design remains, and it is easy to chain the components together.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] As part of its toolkit design, Git has a well-defined model of an incomplete merge, and it has multiple algorithms for completing it, culminating in telling the user that it is unable to complete the merge automatically and that manual editing is needed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Aborting operations or backing out changes will leave useless dangling objects in the database.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] These are generally a small fraction of the continuously growing history of wanted objects.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] when enough loose objects have been created in the repository.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git stores each newly created object as a separate file.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Although individually compressed, this takes up a great deal of space and is inefficient.
