[src:pre-commit-framework/git] A corresponding index file is created for each packfile, recording the offset of each object in the packfile.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Newly created objects (with newly added history) are still stored as single objects, and periodic repacking is needed to maintain space efficiency.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The process of packing the repository can be very computationally costly.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] By allowing objects to exist in the repository in a loose but quickly generated format, Git allows the costly pack operation to be deferred until later, when time matters less, e.g., the end of a workday.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] inside, and the file name of the packfile also contains an SHA-1 checksum.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Another property of Git is that it snapshots directory trees of files.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The earliest systems for tracking versions of source code, Source Code Control System (SCCS) and Revision Control System (RCS), worked on individual files and emphasized the space savings to be gained from interleaved deltas (SCCS) or delta encoding (RCS) the (mostly similar) versions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Later revision-control systems maintained this notion of a file having an identity across multiple revisions of a project.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] However, Torvalds rejected this concept.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Consequently, Git does not explicitly record file revision relationships at any level below the source-code tree.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git's primitives are not inherently a source-code management system.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] From this initial design approach, Git has developed the full set of features expected of a traditional SCM, with features mostly being created as needed, then refined and extended over time.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git has two data structures: a mutable *index* (also called *stage* or *cache*) that caches information about the working directory and the next revision to be committed; and an *object database* that stores immutable objects.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The index serves as a connection point between the object database and the working tree.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Each object is identified by a SHA-1 hash of its contents.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git computes the hash and uses this value for the object's name.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The object is put into a directory matching the first two characters of its hash.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The rest of the hash is used as the file name for that object.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git stores each revision of a file as a unique blob.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The relationships between the blobs can be found through examining the tree and commit objects.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Newly added objects are stored in their entirety using zlib compression.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] This can consume a large amount of disk space quickly, so objects can be combined into *packs*, which use delta compression to save space, storing blobs as their changes relative to other blobs.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Additionally, Git stores labels called refs (short for references) to indicate the locations of various commits.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] A *.gitignore* file may be created in a Git repository as a plain text file.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The files listed in the *.gitignore* file will *not* be tracked by Git.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] This feature can be used to ignore files with keys or passwords, various extraneous files, and large files (which GitHub will refuse to upload).
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Every object in the Git database that is not referred to may be cleaned up by using a garbage collection command or automatically.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] An object may be referenced by another object or an explicit reference.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The commands to create, move, and delete references vary.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git (the main implementation in C) is primarily developed on Linux, although it also supports most major operating systems, including the BSDs (DragonFly BSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, and OpenBSD), Solaris, macOS, and Windows.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The first Windows port of Git was primarily a Linux-emulation framework that hosts the Linux version.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Currently, native Windows builds of Git are distributed as 32- and 64-bit installers.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The git official website currently maintains a build of Git for Windows, still using the MSYS2 environment.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The JGit implementation of Git is a pure Java software library, designed to be embedded in any Java application.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] JGit is used in the Gerrit code-review tool, and in EGit, a Git client for the Eclipse IDE.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Go-git is an open-source implementation of Git written in pure Go.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] It is currently used for backing projects as a SQL interface for Git code repositories and providing encryption for Git.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Dulwich is an implementation of Git written in pure Python with support for CPython 3.6 and later and Pypy.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The libgit2 implementation of Git is an ANSI C software library with no other dependencies, which can be built on multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, macOS, and BSD.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] It has bindings for many programming languages, including Ruby, Python, and Haskell.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] As Git is a distributed version control system, it could be used as a server out of the box.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] It is shipped with a built-in command `git daemon` which starts a simple TCP server running on the Git protocol.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Dedicated Git HTTP servers help (amongst other features) by adding access control, displaying the contents of a Git repository via the web interfaces, and managing multiple repositories.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Already existing Git repositories can be cloned and shared to be used by others as a centralized repo.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] It can also be accessed via remote shell just by having the Git software installed and allowing a user to log in.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git servers typically listen on TCP port 9418.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] For Web-based repository browsing, Git is also shipped with gitweb, a CGI-based interface for viewing repository contents over HTTP.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] There are many offerings of Git repositories as a service.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The most popular are GitHub, SourceForge, Bitbucket and GitLab.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git GUI clients offer a graphical user interface (GUI) to simplify interaction with Git repositories.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] These GUIs provide visual representations of project history, including branches, commits, and file changes.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] They also streamline actions like staging changes, creating commits, and managing branches.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Visual diff tools help resolve merge conflicts arising from concurrent development.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git comes with a Tcl/Tk GUI, which allows users to perform actions such as creating and amending commits, creating and merging branches, and interacting with remote repositories.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] In addition to the official GUI, many third-party interfaces exist that provide similar features to the official GUI distributed with Git.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] GUI clients make Git easier to learn and use, improving workflow efficiency and reducing errors.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Open-source directory Open Hub reported a similar uptake among open-source projects.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git was the overwhelming favorite of responding developers in these surveys, reporting as high as 93.9% in 2022.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The UK IT jobs website itjobswatch.co.uk reports that as of late September 2016, 29.27% of UK permanent software development job openings have cited Git, ahead of 12.17% for Microsoft Team Foundation Server, 10.60% for Subversion, 1.30% for Mercurial, and 0.48% for Visual SourceSafe.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] There are many *Git extensions*, like Git LFS, which started as an extension to Git in the GitHub community and is now widely used by other repositories.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Extensions are usually independently developed and maintained by different people, but at some point in the future, a widely used extension can be merged with Git.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Microsoft developed the Virtual File System for Git (VFS for Git; formerly Git Virtual File System or GVFS) extension to handle the size of the Windows source-code tree as part of their 2017 migration from Perforce.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] VFS for Git allows cloned repositories to use placeholders whose contents are downloaded only once a file is accessed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git can be used in a variety of different ways, but some conventions are commonly adopted.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git does not provide access-control mechanisms, but was designed for operation with other tools that specialize in access control.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] On 17 December 2014, an exploit was found affecting the Windows and macOS versions of the Git client.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] An attacker could also modify the *.git/config* configuration file, which allows the attacker to create malicious Git aliases (aliases for Git commands or external commands) or modify extant aliases to execute malicious commands when run.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The vulnerability was patched in version 2.2.1 of Git, released on 17 December 2014, and announced the next day.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Git version 2.6.1, released on 29 September 2015, contained a patch for a security vulnerability (CVE-2015-7545) that allowed arbitrary code execution.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] The vulnerability was exploitable if an attacker could convince a victim to clone a specific URL, as the arbitrary commands were embedded in the URL.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] An attacker could use the exploit via a man-in-the-middle attack if the connection was unencrypted, as they could redirect the user to a URL of their choice.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Recursive clones were also vulnerable, since they allowed the controller of a repository to specify arbitrary URLs via the gitmodules file.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Linus Torvalds has responded that the hash was mostly to guard against accidental corruption, and the security a cryptographically secure hash gives was just an accidental side effect, with the main security being signing elsewhere.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] Since a demonstration of the SHAttered attack against Git in 2017, Git was modified to use an SHA-1 variant resistant to this attack.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] A plan for hash function transition is being written since February 2020.
[src:pre-commit-framework/git] "Git" is a registered word trademark of Software Freedom Conservancy, registered with the United States Patent and Trademark Office as Registration Number 4680534 since 2015-02-03.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] In computer programming, **hooking** is a range of techniques used to alter or augment the behaviour of an operating system, of applications, or of other software components by intercepting function calls or messages or events passed between software components.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Code that handles such intercepted function calls, events or messages is called a **hook**.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Hook methods are of particular importance in the template method pattern where common code in an abstract class can be augmented by custom code in a subclass.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] In this case each hook method is defined in the abstract class with an empty implementation which then allows a different implementation to be supplied in each concrete subclass.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Hooking is used for many purposes, including debugging and extending functionality.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Examples might include intercepting keyboard or mouse event messages before they reach an application, or intercepting operating system calls in order to monitor behavior or modify the function of an application or other component.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] It is also widely used in benchmarking programs, for example frame rate measuring in 3D games, where the output and input is done through hooking.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Hooking can also be used by malicious code.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] For example, rootkits, pieces of software that try to make themselves invisible by faking the output of API calls that would otherwise reveal their existence, often use hooking techniques.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Typically hooks are inserted while software is already running, but hooking is a tactic that can also be employed prior to the application being started.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Both these techniques are described in greater detail below.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Hooking can be achieved by modifying the source of the executable or library before an application is running, through techniques of reverse engineering.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] This is typically used to intercept function calls to either monitor or replace them entirely.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] For example, by using a disassembler, the entry point of a function within a module can be found.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] It can then be altered to instead dynamically load some other library module and then have it execute desired methods within that loaded library.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] If applicable, another related approach by which hooking can be achieved is by altering the import table of an executable.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] This table can be modified to load any additional library modules as well as changing what external code is invoked when a function is called by the application.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] An alternative method for achieving function hooking is by intercepting function calls through a wrapper library.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] A wrapper is a version of a library that an application loads, with all the same functionality of the original library that it will replace.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] That is, all the functions that are accessible are essentially the same between the original and the replacement.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] This wrapper library can be designed to call any of the functionality from the original library, or replace it with an entirely new set of logic.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The GNU Linker supports the `--wrap=foo` CLI option.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] When used, the linker replaces all calls to `foo` with calls to `__wrap_foo`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The original definition of `foo` can now be referenced with the symbol `__real_foo`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Since this method does not use the dynamic linker, this method can only be used when a program's source code is available and the linking step of the build can be modified.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Operating systems and software may provide the means to easily insert event hooks at runtime.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] It is available provided that the process inserting the hook is granted enough permission to do so.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Microsoft Windows for example, allows users to insert hooks that can be used to process or modify system events and application events for dialogs, scrollbars, and menus as well as other items.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] It also allows a hook to insert, remove, process or modify keyboard and mouse events.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Linux provides another example where hooks can be used in a similar manner to process network events within the kernel through NetFilter.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] When such functionality is not provided, a special form of hooking employs intercepting the library function calls made by a process.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Function hooking is implemented by changing the very first few code instructions of the target function to jump to an injected code.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Alternatively on systems using the shared library concept, the interrupt vector table or the import descriptor table can be modified in memory.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Essentially these tactics employ the same ideas as those of source modification, but instead altering instructions and structures located in the memory of a process once it is already running.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Whenever a class defines/inherits a virtual function (or method), compilers add a hidden member variable to the class which points to a virtual method table (VMT or Vtable).
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Most compilers place the hidden VMT pointer at the first 4 bytes of every instance of the class.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] A VMT is basically an array of pointers to all the virtual functions that instances of the class may call.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] At runtime these pointers are set to point to the right functions, because at compile time, it is not yet known if the base function is to be called or if an overridden version of the function from a derived class is to be called (thereby allowing for polymorphism).
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Therefore, virtual functions can be hooked by replacing the pointers to them within any VMT that they appear.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The code below shows an example of a typical VMT hook in Microsoft Windows, written in C++.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] All virtual functions must be class member functions, and all (non-static) class member functions are called with the __thiscall calling convention (unless the member function takes a variable number of arguments, in which case it is called with __cdecl).
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The __thiscall calling convention passes a pointer to the calling class instance (commonly referred to as a "this" pointer) via the ECX register (on the x86 architecture).
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Therefore, in order for a hook function to properly intercept the "this" pointer that is passed and take it as an argument, it must look into the ECX register.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] In the above example, this is done by setting the hook function (hkVirtualFn1) to use the __fastcall calling convention, which causes the hook function to look into the ECX register for one of its arguments.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Also note that, in the above example, the hook function (hkVirtualFn1) is not a member function itself so it cannot use the __thiscall calling convention. __fastcall has to be used instead because it is the only other calling convention that looks into the ECX register for an argument.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The following example will hook into keyboard events in Microsoft Windows using the Microsoft .NET Framework.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The following source code is an example of an API/function hooking method which hooks by overwriting the first six bytes of a destination function with a JMP instruction to a new function.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The code is compiled into a DLL file then loaded into the target process using any method of DLL injection.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] Using a backup of the original function one might then restore the first six bytes again so the call will not be interrupted.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] In this example the win32 API function MessageBoxW is hooked.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] This example shows how to use hooking to alter network traffic in the Linux kernel using Netfilter.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The following code demonstrates how to hook functions that are imported from another module.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] This can be used to hook functions in a different process from the calling process.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] For this the code must be compiled into a DLL file then loaded into the target process using any method of DLL injection.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The advantage of this method is that it is less detectable by antivirus software and/or anti-cheat software, one might make this into an external hook that doesn't make use of any malicious calls.
[src:pre-commit-framework/hooking] The Portable Executable header contains the Import Address Table (IAT), which can be manipulated as shown in the source below.
