[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Git hook scripts are useful for identifying simple issues before submission to code review.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] We run our hooks on every commit to automatically point out issues in code such as missing semicolons, trailing whitespace, and debug statements.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] By pointing these issues out before code review, this allows a code reviewer to focus on the architecture of a change while not wasting time with trivial style nitpicks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] As we created more libraries and projects we recognized that sharing our pre-commit hooks across projects is painful.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] We copied and pasted unwieldy bash scripts from project to project and had to manually change the hooks to work for different project structures.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] We believe that you should always use the best industry standard linters.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Some of the best linters are written in languages that you do not use in your project or have installed on your machine.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] For example scss-lint is a linter for SCSS written in Ruby.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If you’re writing a project in node you should be able to use scss-lint as a pre-commit hook without adding a Gemfile to your project or understanding how to get scss-lint installed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] We built pre-commit to solve our hook issues.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] It is a multi-language package manager for pre-commit hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] You specify a list of hooks you want and pre-commit manages the installation and execution of any hook written in any language before every commit. pre-commit is specifically designed to not require root access.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If one of your developers doesn’t have node installed but modifies a JavaScript file, pre-commit automatically handles downloading and building node to run eslint without root.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Before you can run hooks, you need to have the pre-commit package manager installed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Once you have pre-commit installed, adding pre-commit plugins to your project is done with the `.pre-commit-config.yaml` configuration file.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Add a file called `.pre-commit-config.yaml` to the root of your project.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The pre-commit config file describes what repositories and hooks are installed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The repository mapping tells pre-commit where to get the code for the hook from.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook mapping configures which hook from the repository is used and allows for customization.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] All optional keys will receive their default from the repository's configuration.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This configuration says to download the pre-commit-hooks project and run its trailing-whitespace hook.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] You can update your hooks to the latest version automatically by running `pre-commit autoupdate`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] By default, this will bring the hooks to the latest tag on the default branch.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Run `pre-commit install` to install pre-commit into your git hooks. pre-commit will now run on every commit.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Every time you clone a project using pre-commit running `pre-commit install` should always be the first thing you do.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If you want to manually run all pre-commit hooks on a repository, run `pre-commit run --all-files`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] To run individual hooks use `pre-commit run <hook_id>`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The first time pre-commit runs on a file it will automatically download, install, and run the hook.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Note that running a hook for the first time may be slow.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] For example: If the machine does not have node installed, pre-commit will download and build a copy of node.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] pre-commit currently supports hooks written in many languages.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] As long as your git repo is an installable package (gem, npm, pypi, etc.) or exposes an executable, it can be used with pre-commit.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Each git repo can support as many languages/hooks as you want.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook must exit nonzero on failure or modify files.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Since the `repo` property of `.pre-commit-config.yaml` can refer to anything that `git clone ...` understands, it's often useful to point it at a local directory while developing hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-commit try-repo` streamlines this process by enabling a quick way to try out a repository.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] a commit is not necessary to `try-repo` on a local directory.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-commit` will clone any tracked uncommitted changes.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must contain an `environment.yml` file which will be used via `conda env create --file environment.yml ...` to create the environment.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `conda` language also supports `additional_dependencies` and will pass any of the values directly into `conda install`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This language can therefore be used with local hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `mamba` or `micromamba` can be used to install instead via the `PRE_COMMIT_USE_MAMBA=1` or `PRE_COMMIT_USE_MICROMAMBA=1` environment variables.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must have a `.pre-commit-channel` folder and that folder must contain the coursier application descriptors for the hook to install.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] For configuring coursier hooks, your `entry` should correspond to an executable installed from the repository's `.pre-commit-channel` folder.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] pre-commit also supports the `coursier` naming of the package manager executable.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must have a `pubspec.yaml` -- this must contain an `executables` section which will list the binaries that will be available after installation.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-commit` will build each executable using `dart compile exe bin/{executable}.dart`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must have a `Dockerfile`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] It will be installed via `docker build .`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Running Docker hooks requires a running Docker engine on your host.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] For configuring Docker hooks, your `entry` should correspond to an executable inside the Docker container, and will be used to override the default container entrypoint.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Your Docker `CMD` will not run when pre-commit passes a file list as arguments to the run container command.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Docker allows you to use any language that's not supported by pre-commit as a builtin.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] pre-commit will automatically mount the repository source as a volume using `-v $PWD:/src:rw,Z` and set the working directory using `--workdir /src`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] See this repository for an example Docker-based hook.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] A more lightweight approach to `docker` hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `docker_image` "language" uses existing docker images to provide hook executables.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `docker_image` hooks can be conveniently configured as local hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `entry` specifies the docker tag to use.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If an image has an `ENTRYPOINT` defined, nothing special is needed to hook up the executable.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If the container does not specify an `ENTRYPOINT` or you want to change the entrypoint you can specify it as well in your `entry`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] dotnet hooks are installed using the system installation of the dotnet CLI.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Hook repositories must contain a dotnet CLI tool which can be `pack`ed and `install`ed as per this example.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `entry` should match an executable created by building the repository.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Additional dependencies are not currently supported.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] A lightweight `language` to forbid files by filename.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `fail` language is especially useful for local hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `entry` will be printed when the hook fails.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] It is suggested to provide a brief description for `name` and more verbose fix instructions in `entry`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must contain go source code.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] It will be installed via `go install ./...`. pre-commit will create an isolated `GOPATH` for each hook and the `entry` should match an executable which will get installed into the `GOPATH`'s `bin` directory.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This language supports `additional_dependencies` and will pass any of the values directly to `go install`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must have one or more `*.cabal` files.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Once installed the `executable`s from these packages will be available to use with `entry`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This language supports `additional_dependencies` so it can be used as a `repo: local` hook.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] For configuring julia hooks, your `entry` should be a path to a julia source file relative to the hook repository (optionally with arguments).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Hooks run in an isolated package environment defined by a `Project.toml` file (optionally with a `Manifest.toml` file) in the hook repository.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If no `Project.toml` file is found the hook is run in an empty environment.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Julia hooks support `additional_dependencies` which can be used to augment, or override, the existing environment in the hooks repository.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This also means that julia can be used as a `repo: local` hook.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `additional_dependencies` are passed to `pkg> add` and should be specified using Pkg REPL mode syntax.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Lua hooks are installed with the version of Lua that is used by Luarocks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must have a `package.json`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] It will be installed via `npm install .`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The installed package will provide an executable that will match the `entry` – usually through `bin` in package.json.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Perl hooks are installed using the system installation of cpan, the CPAN package installer that comes with Perl.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Hook repositories must have something that `cpan` supports, typically `Makefile.PL` or `Build.PL`, which it uses to install an executable to use in the `entry` definition for your hook.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The repository will be installed via `cpan -T .` (with the installed files stored in your pre-commit cache, not polluting other Perl installations).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] When specifying `additional_dependencies` for Perl, you can use any of the install argument formats understood by `cpan`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must be installable via `pip install .` (usually by either `setup.py` or `pyproject.toml`).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The installed package will provide an executable that will match the `entry` – usually through `console_scripts` or `scripts` in setup.py.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This language also supports `additional_dependencies` so it can be used with local hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The specified dependencies will be appended to the `pip install` command.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This hook repository must have a `renv.lock` file that will be restored with `renv::restore()` on hook installation.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If the repository is an R package (i.e. has `Type: Package` in `DESCRIPTION`), it is installed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The supported syntax in `entry` is `Rscript -e {expression}` or `Rscript path/relative/to/hook/root`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The R Startup process is skipped (emulating `--vanilla`), as all configuration should be exposed via `args` for maximal transparency and portability.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] When specifying `additional_dependencies` for R, you can use any of the install argument formats understood by `renv::install()`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must have a `*.gemspec`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] It will be installed via `gem build *.gemspec && gem install *.gem`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The installed package will produce an executable that will match the `entry` – usually through `executables` in your gemspec.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Rust hooks are installed using Cargo, Rust's official package manager.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Hook repositories must have a `Cargo.toml` file which produces at least one binary (example), whose name should match the `entry` definition for your hook.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The repo will be installed via `cargo install --bins` (with the binaries stored in your pre-commit cache, not polluting your user-level Cargo installations).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] pre-commit will bootstrap `rust` if it is not present.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The hook repository must have a `Package.swift`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] It will be installed via `swift build -c release`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] A cross-platform python implementation of `grep` – pygrep hooks are a quick way to write a simple hook which prevents commits by file matching.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `entry` may be any python regular expression.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] For case insensitive regexes you can apply the `(?i)` flag as the start of your entry, or use `args: [-i]`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] For multiline matches, use `args: [--multiline]`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] To require all files to match, use `args: [--negate]`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] System hooks provide a way to write hooks for system-level executables which don't have a supported language above (or have special environment requirements that don't allow them to run in isolation such as pylint).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This hook type will not be given a virtual environment to work with – if it needs additional dependencies the consumer must install them manually.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Script hooks provide a way to write simple scripts which validate files.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `entry` should be a path relative to the root of the hook repository.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Auto-update pre-commit config to the latest repos' versions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] pre-commit will preferentially pick tags containing a `.` if there are ties.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-commit` keeps a cache of installed hook repositories which grows over time.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This command can be run periodically to clean out unused repos from the cache directory.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Install hook script in a directory intended for use with `git config init.templateDir`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Now whenever a repository is cloned or created, it will have the hooks set up already!
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-commit install` will install hooks from `default_install_hook_types` if `--hook-type` is not specified on the command line.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Install all missing environments for the available hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Unless this command or `install --install-hooks` is executed, each hook's environment is created the first time the hook is called.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Each hook is initialized in a separate environment appropriate to the language the hook is written in.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This command does not install the pre-commit script.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] To install the script along with the hook environments in one command, use `pre-commit install --install-hooks`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Migrate list configuration to the new map configuration format.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Produce a sample `.pre-commit-config.yaml`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Try the hooks in a repository, useful for developing new hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `try-repo` can also be used for testing out a repository before adding it to your configuration.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `try-repo` prints a configuration it generates based on the remote hook repository before running the hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] By default, if you have existing hooks `pre-commit install` will install in a migration mode which runs both your existing hooks and hooks for pre-commit.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] To disable this behavior, pass `-f` / `--overwrite` to the `install` command.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If you decide not to use pre-commit, `pre-commit uninstall` will restore your hooks to the state prior to installation.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Not all hooks are perfect so sometimes you may need to skip execution of one or more hooks. pre-commit solves this by querying a `SKIP` environment variable.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `SKIP` environment variable is a comma separated list of hook ids.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This allows you to skip a single hook instead of `--no-verify`ing the entire commit.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] pre-commit supports many different types of `git` hooks (not just `pre-commit`!).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Providers of hooks can select which git hooks they run on by setting the `stages` property in `.pre-commit-hooks.yaml` -- this can also be overridden by setting `stages` in `.pre-commit-config.yaml`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If `stages` is not set in either of those places the default value will be pulled from the top-level `default_stages` option (which defaults to *all* stages).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] By default, tools are enabled for every hook type that pre-commit supports.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The `manual` stage (via `stages: [manual]`) is a special stage which will not be automatically triggered by any `git` hook -- this is useful if you want to add a tool which is not automatically run, but is run on demand using `pre-commit run --hook-stage manual [hookid]`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If you are authoring a tool, it is usually a good idea to provide an appropriate `stages` property.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] For example a reasonable setting for a linter or code formatter would be `stages: [pre-commit, pre-merge-commit, pre-push, manual]`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] To install `pre-commit` for particular git hooks, pass `--hook-type` to `pre-commit install`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Additionally, one can specify a default set of git hook types to be installed for by setting the top-level `default_install_hook_types`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `commit-msg` hooks will be passed a single filename -- this file contains the current contents of the commit message to be validated.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] The commit will be aborted if there is a nonzero exit code.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] post-checkout hooks run *after* a `checkout` has occurred and can be used to set up or manage state in the repository.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `post-checkout` hooks do not operate on files so they must be set as `always_run: true` or they will always be skipped.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `post-commit` runs after the commit has already succeeded so it cannot be used to prevent the commit from happening.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `post-commit` hooks do not operate on files so they must be set as `always_run: true` or they will always be skipped.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `post-merge` runs after a successful `git merge`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `post-merge` hooks do not operate on files so they must be set as `always_run: true` or they will always be skipped.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `post-rewrite` runs after a git command which modifies history such as `git commit --amend` or `git rebase`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `post-rewrite` hooks do not operate on files so they must be set as `always_run: true` or they will always be skipped.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-commit` is triggered before the commit is finalized to allow checks on the code being committed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Running hooks on unstaged changes can lead to both false-positives and false-negatives during committing. pre-commit only runs on the staged contents of files by temporarily stashing the unstaged changes while running hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-merge-commit` fires after a merge succeeds but before the merge commit is created.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This hook runs on all staged files from the merge.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Note that you need to be using at least git 2.24 for this hook.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-rebase` is triggered before a rebase occurs.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] A hook failure can cancel a rebase from occurring.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-rebase` hooks do not operate on files so they must be set as `always_run: true` or they will always be skipped.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `prepare-commit-msg` hooks will be passed a single filename -- this file may be empty or it could contain the commit message from `-m` or from other templates.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `prepare-commit-msg` hooks can modify the contents of this file to change what will be committed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] A hook may want to check for `GIT_EDITOR=:` as this indicates that no editor will be launched.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If a hook exits nonzero, the commit will be aborted.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] Sometimes hooks require arguments to run correctly.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This will pass `--max-line-length=131` to `flake8`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] If you are writing your own custom hook, your hook should expect to receive the `args` value and then a list of staged files.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] When creating local hooks, there's no reason to put command arguments into `args` as there is nothing which can override them -- instead put your arguments directly in the hook `entry`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] You can configure repository-local hooks by specifying the `repo` as the sentinel `local`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] local hooks can use any language which supports `additional_dependencies` or `docker_image` / `fail` / `pygrep` / `unsupported` / `unsupported_script`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] This enables you to install things which previously would require a trivial mirror repository.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] A `local` hook must define `id`, `name`, `language`, `entry`, and `files` / `types` as specified under Creating new hooks.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] `pre-commit` provides several hooks which are useful for checking the pre-commit configuration itself.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p01] These can be enabled using `repo: meta`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] pre-commit provides a few `entry` prefix "helpers" for unusual situations.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] in case it's not clear, using these is *usually* a bad idea.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] for "monorepo" usage one can use this to target a subdirectory.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] it's a bad idea to introduce warning noise but this gives you a way to do it.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] git 2.54 introduced a new way to install git hook tools via `git config`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] `pre-commit init-templatedir` can be used to set up a skeleton for `git`'s `init.templateDir` option.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] This means that any newly cloned repository will automatically have the hooks set up without the need to run `pre-commit install`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] To configure, first set `git`'s `init.templateDir` -- in this example I'm using `~/.git-template` as my template directory.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Now whenever you clone a pre-commit enabled repo, the hooks will already be set up!
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] To still require opt-in, but prompt the user to set up pre-commit use a template hook as follows (for example in `~/.git-template/hooks/pre-commit`).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Filtering with `types` provides several advantages over traditional filtering with `files`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] `types` is specified per hook as an array of tags.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] The tags are discovered through a set of heuristics by the identify library.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] `identify` was chosen as it is a small portable pure python library.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] If a file extension you use is not supported, please submit a pull request!
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] `types`, `types_or`, and `files` are evaluated together with `AND` when filtering.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Tags within `types` are also evaluated using `AND`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Tags within `types_or` are evaluated using `OR`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] will match a file `foo/1.py` but will not match `setup.py`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] will match any of `foo/bar.js` / `foo/bar.jsx` / `foo/bar.ts` / `foo/bar.tsx` but not `baz.js`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] If you want to match a file path that isn't included in a `type` when using an existing hook you'll need to revert back to `files` only matching by overriding the `types` setting.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] With `types: python`, an `exe` starting with `#!/usr/bin/env python3` will also be matched.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] As with `files` and `exclude`, you can also exclude types if necessary using `exclude_types`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] The patterns for `files` and `exclude` are python regular expressions and are matched with `re.search`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] As such, you can use any of the features that python regexes support.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] If you find that your regular expression is becoming unwieldy due to a long list of excluded / included things, you may find a verbose regular expression useful.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] One can enable this with yaml's multiline literals and the `(?x)` regex flag.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Sometimes you only want to run the hooks on a specific version of the language.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] For each language, they default to using the system installed language (So for example if I’m running `python3.7` and a hook specifies `python`, pre-commit will run the hook using `python3.7`).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Sometimes you don’t want the default system installed version so you can override this on a per-hook basis by setting the `language_version`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] This tells pre-commit to use ruby `2.1.5` to run the `scss-lint` hook.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] you can set `default_language_version` at the top level in your configuration to control the default versions across all hooks of a language.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] you can add a badge to your repository to show your contributors / users that you use pre-commit!
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] pre-commit can also be used as a tool for continuous integration.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] For instance, adding `pre-commit run --all-files` as a CI step will ensure everything stays in tip-top shape.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] no additional configuration is needed to run in pre-commit.ci!
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] note: azure pipelines uses immutable caches so the python version and `.pre-commit-config.yaml` hash must be included in the cache key. for a repository template, see [email protected].
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] See the Gitlab caching best practices to fine tune the cache scope.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] pre-commit's cache requires to be served from a constant location between the different builds.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] This isn't the default when using k8s runners on GitLab.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] tox is useful for configuring test / CI tools such as pre-commit.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] One feature of `tox>=2` is it will clear environment variables such that tests are more reproducible.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Under some conditions, pre-commit requires a few environment variables and so they must be allowed to be passed through.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] `pre-commit` configuration aims to give a repeatable and fast experience and therefore intentionally doesn't provide facilities for "unpinned latest version" for hook repositories.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Instead, `pre-commit` provides tools to make it easy to upgrade to the latest versions with `pre-commit autoupdate`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] If you need the absolute latest version of a hook (instead of the latest tagged version), pass the `--bleeding-edge` parameter to `autoupdate`.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] `pre-commit` assumes that the value of `rev` is an immutable ref (such as a tag or SHA) and will cache based on that.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Using a branch name (or `HEAD`) for the value of `rev` is not supported and will only represent the state of that mutable ref at the time of hook installation (and will *NOT* update automatically).
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] We’re looking to grow the project and get more contributors especially to support more languages/versions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] We’d also like to get the .pre-commit-hooks.yaml files added to popular linters without maintaining forks / mirrors.
[src:pre-commit-framework/pre-commit-com-p02] Feel free to submit bug reports, pull requests, and feature requests.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] A **text editor** is interactive software that allows a user to edit plain text, such as Notepad.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] As source code is text, any text editor can be used to edit code, but a source-code editor is designed with features specifically intended for editing code.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some provide integration with software development tools and provide a debugging environment.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] There are important differences between plain text (created and edited by text editors) and rich text (such as that created by word processors or desktop publishing software).
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Plain text exclusively consists of character representation.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Each character is represented by a fixed-length sequence of one, two, or four bytes, or as a variable-length sequence of one to four bytes, in accordance to specific character encoding conventions, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 2022, Shift JIS, UTF-8, or UTF-16.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] These conventions define many printable characters, but also non-printing characters that control the flow of the text, such as space, line break, and page break.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Plain text contains no other information about the text itself, not even the character encoding convention employed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Plain text is stored in text files, although text files do not exclusively store plain text.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Since the early days of computers, plain text was (once by necessity and now by convention) generally displayed using a monospaced font, such that horizontal alignment and columnar formatting were sometimes done using whitespace characters.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Rich text can be saved in binary format (e.g.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] DOC), text files adhering to a markup language (e.g.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] RTF or HTML), or in a hybrid form of both (e.g.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Text editors are intended to open and save text files containing either plain text or anything that can be interpreted as plain text, including the markup for rich text or the markup for something else (e.g.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Before text editors existed, computer text was punched into cards with keypunch machines.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Physical boxes of these thin cardboard cards were then inserted into a card reader.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Magnetic tape, drum and disk card image files created from such card decks often had no line-separation characters at all, and assumed fixed-length 80- or 90-character records.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] An alternative to cards was Punched tape.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] It could be created by some teleprinters (such as the Teletype), which used special characters to indicate ends of records.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some early operating systems included batch text editors, either integrated with language processors or as separate utility programs; one early example was the ability to edit SQUOZE source files for SCAT in the SHARE Operating System.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] The first interactive text editors were "line editors" oriented to teletypes: teleprinter-style or typewriter-style terminals that mechanically printed both input and output on the same continuous roll of paper, without an illuminated display.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Commands (often a single keystroke) effected edits to a file at an insertion point, that the operator needed to keep track of, called the "cursor".
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Edits were verified by typing a command to print a small section of the file, and periodically by printing the entire file.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] In some line editors, the cursor could be moved by commands that specified the line number in the file, text strings (context) for which to search, and eventually regular expressions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Line editors were major improvements over keypunching.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some line editors could be used by keypunch; editing commands could be taken from a deck of cards and applied to a specified file.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some common line editors supported a "verify" mode in which change commands displayed the altered lines.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] An example configuration, circa 1975, was a Teletype Model 33 as a console to a PDP-11 using Version 6 Unix, manipulating text with the *ed*, the standard UNIX text editor.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] When computer terminals with video screens became available, screen-based text editors (sometimes called just "screen editors") became common.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] One of the earliest full-screen editors was O26, which was written for the operator console of the CDC 6000 series computers in 1967.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Another early full-screen editor was vi.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Written in the 1970s, it is still a standard editor on Unix and Linux operating systems.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Also written in the 1970s was the UCSD Pascal Screen Oriented Editor, which was optimized both for indented source code and general text.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Emacs, one of the first free and open-source software projects, is another early full-screen or real-time editor, one that was ported to many systems.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] The 1977 Commodore PET was the first mass-market computer to feature a full-screen editor.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] A full-screen editor's ease-of-use and speed (compared to the line-based editors) motivated many early purchases of video terminals.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] The core data structure in a text editor is the one that manages the string (sequence of characters) or list of records that represents the current state of the file being edited.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] While the former could be stored in a single long consecutive array of characters, the desire for text editors that could more quickly insert text, delete text, and undo/redo previous edits led to the development of more complicated sequence data structures.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] A typical text editor uses a gap buffer, a linked list of lines (as in PaperClip), a piece table, or a rope, as its sequence data structure.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some text editors are small and simple, while others offer broad and complex functions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] For example, Unix and Unix-like operating systems have the pico editor (or a variant), but many also include the vi and Emacs editors.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Microsoft Windows systems come with the simple Notepad, though many people—especially programmers—prefer other editors with more features.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Under Apple Macintosh's classic Mac OS there was the native TeachText later replaced by SimpleText in 1994, which was replaced in Mac OS X by TextEdit, which combines features of a text editor with those typical of a word processor such as rulers, margins and multiple font selection.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] These features are not available simultaneously, but must be switched by user command, or through the program automatically determining the file type.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Most word processors can read and write files in plain text format, allowing them to open files saved from text editors.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Saving these files from a word processor, however, requires ensuring the file is written in plain text format, and that any text encoding or BOM settings will not obscure the file for its intended use.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Non-WYSIWYG word processors, such as WordStar, are more easily pressed into service as text editors, and in fact were commonly used as such during the 1980s.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] The default file format of these word processors often resembles a markup language, with the basic format being plain text and visual formatting achieved using non-printing control characters or escape sequences.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Later word processors like Microsoft Word store their files in a binary format and are almost never used to edit plain text files.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some text editors can edit unusually large files such as log files or an entire database placed in a single file.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Simpler text editors may just read files into the computer's main memory.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] With larger files, this may be a slow process, and the entire file may not fit.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some text editors do not let the user start editing until this read-in is complete.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Editing performance also often suffers in nonspecialized editors, with the editor taking seconds or even minutes to respond to keystrokes or navigation commands.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Specialized editors have optimizations such as only storing the visible portion of large files in memory, improving editing performance.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some editors are programmable, meaning, e.g., they can be customized for specific uses.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] With a programmable editor it is easy to automate repetitive tasks or, add new functionality or even implement a new application within the framework of the editor.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] One common motive for customizing is to make a text editor use the commands of another text editor with which the user is more familiar, or to duplicate missing functionality the user has come to depend on.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Software developers often use editor customizations tailored to the programming language or development environment they are working in.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Emacs can even be programmed to emulate Vi, its rival in the traditional editor wars of Unix culture.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] An important group of programmable editors uses REXX as a scripting language.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] These "orthodox editors" contain a "command line" into which commands and macros can be typed and text lines into which line commands and macros can be typed.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Most such editors are derivatives of ISPF/PDF EDIT or of XEDIT, IBM's flagship editor for VM/SP through z/VM.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Among them are THE, KEDIT, X2, Uni-edit, and SEDIT.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] A text editor written or customized for a specific use can determine what the user is editing and assist the user, often by completing programming terms and showing tooltips with relevant documentation.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Many text editors for software developers include source code syntax highlighting and automatic indentation to make programs easier to read and write.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Programming editors often let the user select the name of an include file, function or variable, then jump to its definition.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some also allow for easy navigation back to the original section of code by storing the initial cursor location or by displaying the requested definition in a popup window or temporary buffer.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Some editors implement this ability themselves, but often an auxiliary utility like ctags is used to locate the definitions.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Most text editors provide methods to duplicate and move text within the file, or between files.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Cut, copy and paste are often integrated with a system clipboard.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Text editors provide extensive facilities for searching and replacing strings of text, either individually, or groups of files in opened tabs or a selected folder.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] , and listing multiple results in one place.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Often—especially with older text editors—there is only one level of edit history remembered and successively issuing the undo command will only "toggle" the last change.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Modern or more complex editors usually provide a multiple-level history such that issuing the undo command repeatedly will revert the document to successively older edits.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] A separate redo command will cycle the edits "forward" toward the most recent changes.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] Ability to jump to a specified line number.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] To define new commands or features as combinations of prior commands or other macros, perhaps with passed parameters, or with nesting of macros.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] To retain options set by the user between editing session.
[src:pre-commit-framework/text-editor] With names specified in, e.g., environment, profile, executed automatically at the beginning of an edit session or when opening a new file.
